Peer evaluation is the process through which people evaluate and offer comments on their peers' work. This might involve assessing the work of students, coworkers, or other members of a group or organization. Peer evaluation may be utilized in a number of situations, including education, where students are requested to evaluate the work of their classmates, and the workplace, where employees are asked to offer comments on the work of their coworkers. Peer evaluation may take many forms, including self-assessment, in which people review their own work, and direct assessment, in which persons evaluate the work of others. It may also be accomplished through many means such as written assessments, verbal comments, or numerical ratings. The primary goal of peer-assessment is to give constructive comments and assist people in identifying their strengths and areas for growth in order to help enhance the quality of their work. It may also be used to encourage peer cooperation, accountability, and mutual understanding, as well as to assist people create a feeling of ownership and responsibility for their work. 